---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import DeliveryDataModel from '../../../components/DeliveryDataModel.jsx';
---

<BaseLayout title="Four Systems, No Single Truth">
  <article>
    <div class="article-container">
      <div class="article-meta">Delivery Intelligence · Part 1</div>
      <h1 class="article-title">Four Systems, No Single Truth</h1>
      <p class="article-subtitle">
        Why tech consultancies struggle to answer the simplest delivery question:
        are we on track, and what has it cost us?
      </p>

      <div class="article-body">
        <h2>The question nobody can answer cleanly</h2>
        <p>
          Every tech consultancy operates with the same fundamental tension. The client
          expects to know whether the engagement is on track — on time, on budget, delivering
          what was promised. The delivery lead wants to know the same thing. And yet, in most
          organisations, answering this question requires manually reconciling data from four
          disconnected systems, each holding a piece of the truth but none telling the whole story.
        </p>
        <p>
          The Statement of Work defines what was promised — milestones, deliverables, and the
          commercial envelope. The Work Breakdown Structure captures the planned decomposition
          and effort estimates. The timesheet system records where hours actually went. And Jira
          or Azure DevOps tracks the real-time flow of work items as the team executes. These
          systems were never designed to talk to each other, and the gaps between them are
          precisely where delivery risk hides.
        </p>

        <h2>Why the gap exists</h2>
        <p>
          The root cause isn't laziness or bad tooling — it's that each system serves a
          different audience with different priorities. The SOW serves the commercial relationship.
          The WBS serves the planning function. Timesheets serve the finance and resourcing teams.
          The backlog serves the delivery team. Each is optimised for its own purpose, and forcing
          them into a single unified view has historically required more overhead than most
          engagements can justify.
        </p>
        <p>
          The result is predictable. Timesheets get coded to high-level phases rather than specific
          deliverables. Work items in the backlog proliferate and evolve in ways that drift from the
          original WBS. Milestones in the SOW are output-based — "deliver the data model" — while
          the backlog is activity-based — "configure pipeline X". And the delivery lead ends up
          relying on gut feel supplemented by whichever system they happen to trust most.
        </p>

        <h2>What it costs you</h2>
        <p>
          This isn't an abstract problem. When you can't trace actuals back to estimates at a
          meaningful level, you lose the ability to detect overruns early. A deliverable that was
          estimated at 200 hours might be consuming 300, but if timesheets are coded to the phase
          level, you won't see it until the phase budget is exhausted — by which point you've lost
          the ability to course-correct.
        </p>
        <p>
          It also creates trust issues at steering committees. When the delivery lead reports
          "we're 70% complete" but can't show the working behind that number, the client is left
          to take it on faith. And faith erodes quickly when milestones start slipping.
        </p>

        <h2>A unified data model</h2>
        <p>
          The solution isn't to replace these systems — each serves its purpose well. The solution
          is a lightweight mapping layer that translates between them, anchored on the unit that
          matters most to the client relationship: the SOW deliverable.
        </p>
        <p>
          Below is an interactive data model that shows how these six entities relate to each other,
          what fields matter, how earned value metrics are derived, and the design principles that
          make it practical rather than theoretical. Click through the tabs to explore each dimension.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Wide component embed -->
    <div class="component-embed">
      <div class="component-embed-inner">
        <DeliveryDataModel client:load />
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="article-container">
      <div class="article-body">
        <h2>The minimum viable starting point</h2>
        <p>
          If your organisation can only implement two things, make it these: every Epic in the
          backlog carries a deliverable_id linking it to the SOW, and every timesheet entry is
          coded to a deliverable_id and an activity category. With just those two data points
          consistently captured, you can calculate earned value, cost variance, and role mix
          variance — which answers 80% of the questions a steering committee will ask.
        </p>
        <p>
          In the next article in this series, we'll take this data model and build an AI agent
          that can query across all four systems, reconcile the data, and produce a delivery
          health dashboard — turning hours of manual reconciliation into a conversation.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
